    <link href="//thimble.webmaker.org/learning_projects/tutorial/tutorial.css" rel="stylesheet">
    <style>
      blockquote {
        margin-left: 2em;
      }
      
      ul {
        padding-left: 2em; 
      }
    </style>
    <!-- these scripts turn your make into a tutorial -->
    <script src="//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js"></script>
    <script src="//thimble.webmaker.org/learning_projects/tutorial/tutorial.js"></script>
    <script>
      jQuery(document).ready(function($){
        $('body').tutorial();
      });
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <!--
      enclose each tutorial step in its own section tags
      you can include any sort of markup, including images
      you can also add more sections

      if you want to attach this tutorial to another make,
      first publish this make
      then tag the other make with prefix "tutorial-" followed by the url for this make
    -->

    <section>
      <h1>Creating a tutorial</h1>
      <p>Create a tutorial by remixing this make. You can also access it <a href="https://thimble.webmaker.org/projects/tutorial">here</a>.</p>
      <p>Modify anything between the <code>section</code> tags (lines 29 - 32). You can include any HTML within these tags.</p>
      <p>Add more <code>section</code> or <code>div</code> elements for additional tutorial steps.</p>
      <p>The make should take care of the rest, like pagination, linking line references, and styling the tutorial nav.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h1>Advanced options</h1>
      <p>You can set options in line 13 for increased control.</p>
      <pre>
  $('body').tutorial({
    pagination: true,
    smartlines: true,
    target: "div"
  });
	  </pre>
      <p>Set pagination to false to show the tutorial as a single page with no nav.</p>
      <p>Set smartlines to false to ignore line references.</p>
      <p>Change 'body' to a different target whose children you want to turn into tutorial steps.</p>
      <p>Set target to any css selector to filter which children you want to use.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h1>Adding the tutorial to a make</h1>
      <p>Tag your make with <code>tutorial-[url]</code>, where <code>[url]</code> is the url to your published tutorial.</p>
      <p>Nearly any webpage will work, including Thimble makes like this one.</p>
      <p>You can attach multiple tutorials.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h1>Tutorials in action</h1>
